  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This dataset explores the landscape of medical-device recalls in the UK, highlighting its significance with 4,631 views and 3,224 downloads, evidencing robust community interest and engagement.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset titled \"Medical-device recalls in the UK and the device-regulation process: retrospective review of safety notices and alerts\" plays a crucial role in understanding the regulatory environment surrounding medical devices. With 4,631 views and 3,224 downloads, it demonstrates notable community engagement, underscoring its technical value and accessibility for further research.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">With proven downstream reuse of the dataset, as indicated by three distinct instances of its application in subsequent research, the authors Heneghan, Thompson, Billingsley, and Cohen have contributed valuable insights that enhance the scientific discourse on medical-device safety. This active reuse signals commitment from the research community to build upon the findings and foster continued investigation into device safety issues.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Although the dataset has not garnered mentions on platforms such as Wikipedia, Reddit, or Bluesky, its academic footprint is reflected in citations from various venues, including Ecology Letters and PLoS ONE. This demonstrates that the dataset is being utilized across different disciplines, indicating a cross-field relevance in understanding medical device regulations.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In terms of geographical impact, the dataset has been cited by research originating from countries including the United States, Mexico, and Argentina, showcasing its international relevance. As such, this contribution enhances the understanding of medical-device recalls beyond the UK, emphasizing its importance in a global context.</p>",
